
<div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
        <h1>Escape Characters in Regular Expressions</h1>
        <p>Escape characters in regular expressions allow you to match special characters or represent non-printable characters. They are often preceded by a backslash (\).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Commonly Used Escape Characters</h2>
            <p>Here are some commonly used escape characters in regular expressions:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>/\d/</code> matches any digit character.</li>
                <li><code>/\w/</code> matches any word character (alphanumeric + underscore).</li>
                <li><code>/\s/</code> matches any whitespace character (space, tab, newline, etc.).</li>
                <li><code>/\./</code> matches a literal period (dot).</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Usage</h2>
            <p>Escape characters are useful when you want to match characters that have special meanings in regular expressions. They help you match specific characters regardless of their special meanings.</p>
            <p>For example, <code>/\d/</code> matches any digit character, and <code>/\//</code> matches a literal forward slash.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">        
        <div class="col-md-12">
            <h2>Example: Matching a Literal Dot</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match a literal dot:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>/\./</code> matches ".".</li>
                <li><code>/\./</code> does not match "a", "1", etc.</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Example: Matching a Backslash</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match a literal backslash:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>/\\</code> matches "\\".</li>
                <li><code>/\\</code> does not match "a", "1", etc.</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Example: Matching Special Characters</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match a specific set of characters:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>/[\/\.\-]/</code> matches "/", ".", or "-".</li>
                <li><code>/[\/\.\-]/</code> does not match "a", "1", etc.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>    
</div>